The Client, Canadian Natural (CNRL) is one of the largest independent crude oil and natural gas producers in the world. The Albian Engineering Information Management team at CNRL has a huge repository of unstructured and complex engineering documents like Professional Work Products (PWPs). It is a requirement from the Association of Professional Engineers and Geosciences of Alberta (APEGA) that authenticated originals or copies of Professional Work Products (PWPs) must be kept for reference or for information against legal claims. Hence, such authenticated engineering documents need to be identified, consolidated and made easily available to the Albian business team. Authenticated documents can be identified by detecting the presence of an engineering stamp in the document. Currently, there is a manual process to identify the authenticated documents, which slows down the entire process of consolidation and making these authenticated documents available to the Albian business team. CNRL wants to leverage the machine learning-based solution to automatically identify such authenticated documents. Quantiphi will develop and deploy a machine learning-based computer vision solution in AWS production environment for assisting the CNRL team to automatically detect the presence of engineering stamp in the documents, consolidate these authenticated documents into a repository and create an index with metadata like filename and Presence or Absence of Engineering Stamp to make it easy for business to search these authenticated documents from the created repository. The following AWS services will be used in this project: SageMaker, DynamoDB, S3, SQS, Lambda, EC2, Route53, Load Balancer, AWS SFTP.
The high-level scope of the India OEM Implementation is to build platform and APIs to integrate with OEM systems in India

Currently, the client builds Machine Learning models on local systems, which need to be deployed and configured manually. This entire process is time-taking and the system is not scalable
Quantiphi is helping the client in the orchestration of training, evaluation, and deployment of over 100 models running on SageMaker by leveraging Apache Airflow. Once each model is deployed, the Production Model Lifecycle is such that the scoring, evaluation, and retraining of the model is automated.
Quantiphi is also helping the client in the visualization of the performance of the deployed models using Amazon QuickSight and Amazon Athena.
Tools/Services: Amazon SageMaker,  Amazon ECR, Amazon CodeCommit, Amazon Systems Manager, Amazon QuickSight, Amazon Athena, Amazon Glue, Amazon EC2, Amazon S3, Amazon RDS, Apache Airflow
Our solution is helping the client to:
Reduce the manual efforts for set-up and configuration
Build generalized templates for deployments with ease
Automated Production Model lifecycle management
Smart insights and Visualization on the performance of models
Improve operational efficiency

Client currently has around 590+ machines/gensets of 2 types(CRDi and Power Car) in multiple locations
IOT devices send sensors data every 30 seconds to Kirloskar Remote Monitoring (KRM) application and data persists in MS SQL Database
Any failure in functioning of the machine is reported by the client, which is logged in Siebel CRM software and necessary next steps are taken
Total data size including archive data for CRDi is ~120 GB since inception and for Power Car it is ~ 60 GB and daily incremental data size is ~ 1 GB in total for both
Currently, client does not have any SLA on predictive maintenance
solution:
Historic data will be utilized to build a predictive solution to raise alerts of non-functional failure to minimize the downtime
Machine Learning models will be trained in Amazon SageMaker using the existing sensor data from KRM application for different machines of CRDi type
These ML models would be deployed on AWS Cloud which will be used to predict the non-functional failures at least 10 hours ahead for CRDi type
Data from CRM will be utilized to train the developed models to rectify the incorrect prediction(false positives) using a feedback loop
